{
  "answer": "**Ghalib's ghazal titled \"Gham khaane mein boda dil-e-nakaam bahut hai\" (ch. 50 of *Diwan-E-Ghalib*) opens with a couplet portraying the heart (*dil*) as an unsuccessful, intoxicated drinker (*boda*) dwelling in the \"tavern of sorrow\" (*gham khaane mein*), where its capacity to endure grief exceeds what's needed—even as the \"rose-red wine\" of sorrow diminishes.[^1]**\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 50 (\"Gham khaane mein boda dil-e-nakaam bahut hai\"), [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/50-gham-khaane-mein-boda-dil-e-nakaam-bahut-hai/translation/#p-b39b6a).  \n`This weak, failed heart's capacity for pain is more than enough; / The grief that rose-red wine is on the wane is more than enough.`",
